metadata.name: Quantum Vacuum #318
metadata.description:
Empty space is not empty. It's filled with energy, transient fluctuations in quantum fields, bubbling with virtual particles popping in and out of existence. 

Part of an ongoing series of work combining my fascination with the fringes of fundamental physics, the emergence of complex behaviour through the interaction of very simple rules, and my obsession with hacking our perceptual systems. 

/Disclaimer: This is not a simulation, but an artistic conceptual interpretation and dramatization. :)

metadata.name: Modular Permutation  #5
metadata.description:
The permutation of sounds and colors tries to understand the natural order of numbers and their forms represented in nature, silence is where that number meets infinity, noise is the movement of air, silence flows like this the chaos of numbers, creating the abstract . this abstract simulation is part of a cultural context and a digital effervescence, where computers are no longer tools and become co-authors in the random factor that simulates chaos in this modular composition, both in image and in sound.

metadata.name: Coloring With Lines #402
metadata.description:
This project started as a way to teach myself more about classes in p5.js by trying to code the "Chaos Game" method of plotting a Serpinski Triangle

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kbKtFN71Lfs

Once figured out, I expanded the method to other shapes to see if different types of fractals might form. They did not, but the result was a series of points that could be connected with thin lines to draw shapes without using the native functions of p5. After working on colors it seemed like a nice enough project to release for free to everyone. Thank you all for your interest and support, hope you get a cool one!

metadata.name: Extreme Ways Sketchup #510
metadata.description:
« Extreme ways are back again..."

This artwork is proposed as a gift for all Extreme Ways owners (at mint time of Extreme Ways Sketchup).
Very few changes in the code with respect to Extreme Ways (mainly freezing or imposing strict limits to main parameters).

It can be viewed as a sketchup of the first steps of Extreme Ways.

Will you keep it ?
Will you sell it (and then earn 25% of royalties) ?
Will you try to get one that looks like your Extreme Ways to get a match ?
It's up to you...

Interaction.
Press h in live mode to list the possibilities.
Key ’s’  : Save an image of the output at the current resolution
Key 1-9 : Change resolution


For Extreme Ways, a guide for interactivity is available :

metadata.name: THE400FLIPS #75
metadata.description:
The more they flip. The more you’ll make.

p5.js –> Blockchain


Controls:

[s] save as PNG.
[a] render alternate higher resolution artwork (takes a few seconds).
[z] save alternate artwork as PNG.


Artist note:

Primary royalties are split 95-5% between artist and The Processing Foundation.

Secondary royalties go to the minters (99.9% of the 15%).

The preview thumbnails don’t do justice to the artworks. Please run the code to appreciate them better. Also, remember to check the alternate higher resolution renders using [a].

Some preview thumbnails might look slightly different to the artwork seen when running the code. This is due to the resolution difference between the capture module and the live code on your device. 

Please get in touch in the event of a blank preview thumbnail. 

Made in p5.js and rendered in webGL. Tested on Chrome and Safari.

metadata.name: Over the Air #33
metadata.description:
During the last couple of decades, over the air television signals and antennas switched to digital, bringing with them a new form of static and distortion as the signal is broken up. "Over the Air" is inspired by these digital distortions, incorporating aspects of them into the same grid-like structure seen on the television. Additional patterns are combined in the grid with these distortions to create the final artwork.

Patterns for the individual blocks in the grid are divided into categories, and various amounts are picked for each work, with dozens of possible mixtures. Patterns can flow in different directions across the varied canvases. Distribution of these patterns across the grid varies from work to work, providing for different feels as they bunch together or spread apart.
